Exploratory Data Analysis with R

By Jason Zmudka

========================================================

This report analyzes a data set of 4898 white wines. Each wines quality was rated by a taster on a scale of 1 to 10. There are also 11 different chemical properties that were measured.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The data consists of 4898 rows and 12 features:

  1. fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)
  2. volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)
  3. citric acid (g / dm^3)
  4. residual sugar (g / dm^3)
  5. chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3
  6. free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
  7. total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
  8. density (g / cm^3)
  9. pH
  10. sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)
  11. alcohol (% by volume)
  12. quality (score between 0 and 10)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Quality is the main feature of the data. It has simple 1-10 rating system. I plan on analyzing the other 11 columns to see how they affect quality level.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest.

I think residual sugar levels and alcohol levels will play a big role. I also can see where having high levels of some characteristics like sulfates and acidity might affect the quality level negatively.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No, the measurements given were very conventional.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The distribution of residual.sugar was highly skewed to the left and had a very long tail. The vast majority of the wines had low sugar but there were some that had higher levels of sugar. I scaled the y variable with log10, and the histogram showed me that there was consistent amount of wines with higher residual sugar.

Looking at the correlation table, there are a few things that stand out. Density strongly correlates with residual sugar and alcohol. Free sulfur dioxide strongly correlates with total sulfur dioxide. Quality, our most important feature, most strongly correlates with alcohol content.

Here we can see the relationship between quality and alcohol content. There are few white wines with a high rating that are low alcohol. The red line is the line of regression.

Looking at this scatter plot, it appears that having a high sugar content makes for a more dense wine.

In this scatter plot, we see that the higher the alcohol content, the lower the density.

As I suspected guessed, alcohol and residual sugar are inversely correlated. The red line is the line of regression.

I used jitter and alpha to show that as expected, there are fewer high quality white wines with high residual sugar. However, there are some white wines with high residual sugar. The red line is the line of regression.

This one surprised me. Although they have similar histogram plots, there is no obvious relationship between fixed acidity and volatile acidity.

I wondered if some factors had an ideal range of values where the quality of the wine would be the highest. Here I sorted total sulfur dioxide values into buckets and plotted the conditional means of the quality factor. As you can see, the sweet spot for total sulfur dioxide is just around 100.

In the description of the data, it says that high levels of volatile acidity would lead to a more vinegar like taste. This box plot shows that high levels of it are definitely less desirable in terms of quality.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Quality has a strongly correlated relationship to alcohol. Many of other factors were inversely correlated to quality indicating that you wouldnt want their levels to be too high. I found that total.sulfur.dioxide had a range where it was best.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

The relationships between residual sugar, alcohol, and density were interesting. Alcohol is less dense than water while adding sugar to water adds density. During the fermentation process, sugar is converted to alcohol, thus the inverted correlation of alcohol to residual sugar.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The relationship of residual sugar to density was most strongly correlated.

Multivariate Plots Section

In this plot, I showed the relationship between different levels of alcohol with residual sugar and density. The lines were noisy, so I rounded alcohol to the nearest whole number and made it into a factor. I also rounded residual sugar in order to get smoother lines.

This scatter plot shows the relationship between total sulfur dioxide and alcohol. Quality is the third factor. It shows that higher quality wines have higher alcohol while lower ones have higher total sulfur dioxide.

This bar graph shows that wines with higher chlorides generally had lower alcohol percentage. It also shows the levels of quality.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I was able to further study the relationship between residual sugar, alcohol, and density. Most wines with higher levels of alcohol appear to have less sugar and are less dense.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Surprisingly wines lower in alcohol were saltier or higher in chlorides and lower in quality.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the strengths and limitations of your model.

I felt that modeling the data was a little beyond the scope of the material. Some of the factors had a middle range where levels were ideal.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

In this visualization, I show that the quality rating of white wines is strongly correlated with alcohol content. Because quality is our key factor, it is important to know this correlation. I used alpha to add some transparency to make it easier to see the less dense areas. I also added a line of regression to clearly show the relationship.

Plot Two

Description Two

Here I wanted to show that some factors have middle range where the quality rating would be highest. I chose total sulfur dioxide because I suspected at some level, the taste of sulfur would have an undesirable effect on quality. I sorted the wines into bins by the total sulfur dioxide factor. Next I plotted a line graph by plotting the conditional means of the quality factor for each bin. I had a lot of noise, so I cleaned it by making fewer points by dividing and rounding the x factor. I trimmed the x axis at 300 because of some outliers. Lastly I used Geom_Smooth to show a nice smooth curve.

Plot Three

Description Three

I wanted to show the three-way relationship between residual sugar, alcohol, and density. I rounded the alcohol levels and made a factor. I plotted a line graph that gives a colored line for each alcohol level. I reduced the noise by rounding the residual sugar factor. Finally I trimmed the x and y axes to get a closer look.

Reflection

The white wine data set that I used was pretty large, nearly 5000 observations. It gave me a good variety of data with a huge amount of average rated wines and many outliers. The biggest flaw I found was in the the main factor, quality. It is based on a rating from 1 to 10 by a median of just three evaluations by wine experts. That is really small number and no other information about the wine experts is given.

It was interesting to find that different chemical components had relationships with the density of the wine. I also found that some factors have a sweet spot where their levels were optimal for higher quality. There is a clear relationship between alcohol level and quality.

I struggled to find relationships between many of the factors. They seemed irrelevant to my analysis. They contributed very little, if not at all, to the main Quality factor. Overall, I think I was successful at discovering the factors that made the biggest difference.

It would be interesting to contrast the white wines with the sister data set of red wines. Im curious to see the chemical differences there are between them. Would red wines generally be higher in density because they are sweeter?
